        <p class="date"><font color="#0000FF" size="4">A LightSeeker's View of 
          the War</font><br>
          <span class="normal">by Wiltan Ryouki of Mithaniel Marr (LightSeekers)</span></p>
        <p class="whitetext9">Upon returning from our honeymoon, Takhi and I were 
          startled to see an army forming at the gates of Neriak. Scores of Tier'Dal, 
          Trolls, and Ogres, as well as fearsome officers in shiny armor or mystical 
          robes stood before their dark elven mistress awaiting orders. </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">Toward the front of the crowd, we saw our friend 
          Histaffu. It was obvious he was caught up in the excitement; a lust 
          for blood showed clearly on his face.</p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"What's going on, friend?" I asked.</p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"War!" he replied. "We're going to war! Will you 
          join us?" </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"You know I can't do that, Histaffu," I replied. 
          "My guild; we stand on the side of goodness. You could have been with 
          us; you can STILL be with us. Give up this nonesense." </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"What? Are you crazy? You won't stand by your own 
          kind?" he asked, astonished. </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"You are my oldest friend, Histaffu, and I would 
          never wish to fight you. But I can't join you in the senseless slaughter 
          of innocents." </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">He pondered for a moment, and then replied, "Wiltan, 
          you are a brother to me, but know this: if you stand with the army of 
          good in this war, I WILL strike you down." </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">I glanced nervously at Takhi, my new bride. In some 
          ways, it still seemed like yesterday when Takhi, Histaffu, Kaedir, and 
          I were the 'Bone Brigade' - four necromancers who, when together, could 
          take on the world. We were barely more than children back then. In Histaffu's 
          rush for power, he embraced darkness and evil. Still, when we saw each 
          other, there was always a hint of his old self about him; he often came 
          to us with fantastic gifts; artifacts he found in his travels. For a 
          moment, it would be like we were the Bone Brigade again. But I realize 
          now; the Histaffu we knew in our youth was gone.</p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"So be it." I said. </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">Takhi and I faded into the crowd and waited to hear 
          more. A rallying cry went up: "To the bridge!" The next sound was like 
          thunder as the army of darkness rushed for the bridge that leads towards 
          the commonlands. War cries were shouted. Wolves and bears were slaughtered 
          simply for being in the way. And an ogre officer in gleaming platemail 
          spoke to me as he ran by. </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"How was the honeymoon, Wiltan?" </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">Takhi and I looked to each other. Neither of us 
          had ever seen the ogre before, and he was leading a battalion of evil 
          forces. How did he know us? And what else did he know? </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">Just then, the young warrior Chithd spoke through 
          the mystical bond all members of the LightSeekers Guild share. "Whoa! 
          I'm at the first orc camp in the commonlands. I was aiding some humans 
          and dwarfs against the orcs, when suddenly, two Tier'Dal Lieutenants 
          appeared from nowhere. They slaughtered everyone except me! I thought 
          I would be next, but after the last human fell, they just returned to 
          their posts by the orcs." </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"Strange. Must be the vanguard of this army. I'm 
          on my way." </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">Creating a mystical gate is child's play to a spellcaster 
          of my ability. In a moment, I stood beside Chithd at the orc camp. At 
          our feet were seven bodies. </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"It all happened so fast. One second we were getting 
          ready to bash the orcs, and the next, I was here alone." He shivered.</p>
        <p class="whitetext9"> "This bodes not well, friend. You were right to 
          contact me. That army can only be headed for the keep at Highpass. I'm 
          going to run ahead and try to warn them. If they don't kill me as soon 
          as they see me, I'll offer the LightSeekers' aid. That army will be 
          passing through here soon; stay alive for now. I'll contact you when 
          I know where we stand." </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">Chithd saluted me solemnly. I nodded. As an afterthought, 
          I quickly wove a spell of protection upon him. Although for what lay 
          ahead, the armor of spirits would hardly be enough.</p>
        <p class="whitetext9">It was a long run to Highpass with much danger along 
          the way. I gathered shadows about me so I could travel unseen. And good 
          that I did; the vanguard of the good army had set up a post at the entrance 
          into Kithicor Woods. I easily passed by them. Through the trees I heard 
          shouting as the army of Tunare prepared for the seige. I pushed myself 
          to run even faster when I heard reports that the army of darkness had 
          already reached the western commonlands. Finally, I reached the entrance 
          to Highpass. I dropped my mystical concealment and stepped into view 
          before the masses there. </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">A hundred swords were drawn like one. Arrows were 
          trained upon me. I could hear magicians chanting, preparing for a magical 
          strike. I did what any brave Tier'Dal necromancer would do. I raised 
          my hands and surrendered. </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">A burly captain in armor that had obviously carried 
          him through many fierce battles stepped forward. "We don't want your 
          kind here, inkie. I don't know what you're up to, but if you are still 
          here at the count of ten, your's will be the first blood my sword tastes 
          tonight! One, two..." </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">I had no time. I shouted as loud as I could, "The 
          LightSeekers wish to help the army of Tunare! You call us evil; we say 
          we are not! Surely you won't turn away aid in the hour of your most 
          desperate need!"</p>
        <p class="whitetext9"> "... eight, nine..."</p>
        <p class="whitetext9"> "Hold!" The voice was clearly feminine, yet filled 
          with authority. A shiver went down my spine as she stepped forward, 
          unmistakable even in her regal armor. She represented everything I had 
          been taught to hate and fear as a child, and everything I sought to 
          embrace and support as an adult. "Stand before me, Wiltan Ryouki of 
          the LightSeekers," said Fiona Vie, Princess of Felwithe. </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"Here I am," I said humbly as I knelt before her. 
        </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"You seek the light, do you?" she asked, "and your 
          guild as well?" </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"We do," I replied. </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"This battle is not the place for you to prove your 
          virtue. It will begin soon; I would leave if I were you." </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"But we wish to help. We are ready to die by your 
          side, if need be," I offered. </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"I feel you speak truly. You say you are ready to 
          die by our sides; are you ready to die by our hands as well? In the 
          frenzy that will undoubtedly ensue, I can offer no protection for your 
          guild. The army of Tunare will slaughter every Tier'Dal, every Ogre, 
          and every Troll they see. There will be nothing I can do to stop them 
          from attacking you as well. </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">"If that happens, my forces are wasting their energies 
          fighting you instead of the true enemy. Your efforts to assist us will 
          actually distract and hinder us instead." </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">I bowed my head. I could see that she was right, 
          but had truly hoped that this war was the opportunity I'd been waiting 
          for to make the LightSeekers be recognized throughout Norrath as a force 
          for good. </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">As if she knew what I was thinking, Fiona spoke 
          again. "Wiltan, if none of your guild interferes in the war ahead, I 
          will entertain the notion of your guild finding the light you seek. 
          But let it be known - if even a single LightSeeker rises up against 
          us, you will NEVER stand before me in Felwithe. Understood?" </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">I nodded, and then saluted the princess. I wasn't 
          sure exactly what she meant. Was she offering to bring us into the light? 
          There was no time to discuss it, though. I bowed to the captain, who 
          was obviously disappointed he wouldn't be decorating his mantle with 
          my scalp. Then I briskly stepped back into the woods. As soon as I was 
          safely away, I summoned shadows around me once again and headed for 
          home. Just as I was nearing the edge of the forest, I heard Fiona's 
          voice shout to her troops. </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">. "Let it be known to all who fight for Tunare - 
          a group calling themselves the LightSeekers has come before me. If their 
          leader speaks true, they are enemies of darkness..." </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">The rest of her speech was cut off by the roar of 
          the approaching army. I did my best simply to get out of the way, and 
          then created another mystical portal to the Commonlands. Chithd was 
          still there, burying his friends. With him were most of the LightSeekers, 
          waiting for my orders. </p>
        <p class="whitetext9">I could see their enthusiasm sink as I told them 
          we were staying out of the war. But after telling the details of my 
          encounter with Fiona Vie, their spirits raised. Perhaps one day we would 
          be outcasts no more... </p>
